reviews.review_text:
great 86 aud... As someone who went to several spring 86 shows, it has largely remained a tour (if not year) that was hard to fully appreciate due to audience recordings that lacked the sonic quality of the auds in circulation from the previous couple of years.   In the past couple of years, that has changed with the addition of new audience recordings of these and other shows from the early-mid 80’s.  (Thank you Charlie Miller).  These allow us to appreciate what we always knew were great shows but couldn’t prove to ourselves or others.  Those days are gone with this and the other great audience recording of this show: gd86-03-25.beyer.connor.3188.sbeok.shnf

Both recordings are great with the Beyer being a closer read and the Mattes providing the full scope of events.  It’s a dreamy, quick opening to the first set but it gets bogged down in discussions pertaining to what in hindsight was possibly going to be the breakout of “Revolutionary Hamstrung Blues” but they seemed to have chickened out.  (They decided to wait and throw it out to me in the deep end of the pool in Portland two nights later).  The first Desolation Row is strong and concise and they finish with a fast Don’t Sleaze. 

At this point in the tour (again, my first stop was the 27th), I don’t think I’d know what to think they might open the second set with.  Logic would tell me they were way past due for a Scarlet>Fire but there was no guarantee of logical outcomes in 85-86.   Watching setlists from a distance at the beginning of this year, I was disappointed at things like the Estimated into Drums in Oaland, and other indicators of what seemed to be a trend in the shortening of show and song length.  Would the novelty breakouts of 85 continue?  Would first sets ever be spacey again?  (Note the lack of reflective, jammy songs in the first sets so far in this tour; even the Supplication>Let it Grow is deceptive: it’s so breakneck they practically break their necks transitioning into it. 

So, you think you’re due Scarlet but at this point you know that Fire is not guaranteed.  The last one they did was in the Meadowlands in November, so it’s kind of a rarity at this point and for the last two East Coast tours, literally left til the final shows.  Alas, the first Scarlet>Fire of the tour is not to happen tonight (spoiler alert: it never does!  The next one isn’t until was not to be this night either, a nice Scarlet though into a serviceable Touch, which was really coming along that year due primarily to Phil’s new approach to it on bass.  

The setlist has a lot of the properties of what sometimes seemed to happen the last night of a run: the sense that they were saving things or doing a short show.  Looks Like Rain>GDTRFB>drums was prob not on anyone’s wishlist, still they are brisk and pleasant enough.  Space is relatively close to the ground too as if they didn’t want to get too far out there before loading the trucks and driving to Maine.  (I know they didn’t load the equipment themselves.)  

Tom Thumb is definitely not expected out of Space, despite happening the previous fall in Worcester.   It’s a confident and fun version though I’m not sure where that town in California is that he mentions.  The post-drums settles into a more conventional vein after that with a reedy Black Peter and careens to an end with an always welcome Lovelight.
